night, nah... it was just the holiday where people are expected to go outside (argh! the day star!  Make it stoppppp...but the boomy things at night look like sparkley spell effects, yes yes) &amp;/or spend time with family, but certainly spend time no where near a computer.<br><br>Skyknight, were you being sarcastic about no one roleplaying with you here?  <br><br>Yes, it is a bit quiet in the lower levels as people get to know you &amp; you get up the courage to get to know people.  In that alone, I would say we don't make it all that easy for people to start on FV.  The excuse generally offered by the high levels for why they don't seek out the younglings for RP is that they are afraid they will have to deal with d00disms.  I think it is more that we are all pretty much more comfortable with our own set of friends (nothing wrong with that) &amp; are shy about seeking out others.<br><br>One thing I have been doing lately... as I pick up a bunch of armor drops (nothing spectacular, just wicker since I was doing some hunting/exploring in the Warrens), I keep a full or nearly full set after selling to the merchant.  Then I go back home (Kelethin) find some youngling hunting in the easy grounds.  I look for the ones who appear to be using their starting weapon &amp; tunic (I don't go inspecting &amp; rarely, if ever, use /who even if I see a blue name... would I know that info so precisely?).  When I see one, I cast my healing on him/her (younglings bleed a lot &amp; fast) &amp; my two buffs, armor &amp; agility.  If I get a &quot;thank you&quot; (not thx) or anything else appropriate, I'll ask if they would like some armor (a few tell me they're broke to which I respond, free of course) and then proceed to give them some protection against the orc pawn, wasps, spiderlings, and the like.  I have also taken to asking them not to kill bears or wolves (unless they really honestly must, like if one is about to kill them).  This has resulted in a few RP conversations with the youngling as well as a few of them (true newbies to the game) asking about how things work (taught a baby ranger to use the bow I just gave him *grin*) in IC or OOC (but generally not in d00disms).  I know I have more patience to deal with the question/answer session of &quot;how does EQ work&quot; than many other players (comes from years as a teacher, I think), so the possiblity of that Q/A stuff might be the other thing giving higher levels pause in contemplating conversing with a youngling.<br><br>I use the &quot;he/she has to say 'thank you' to the healing/buffing&quot; to weed out the d00ds and impolite.  I have found, though, the d00ds usually won't be hunting wasps and bats and pawns and looting each kill.  The d00ds usually have someone who can/will help them move on to bigger prey from about the moment they first appear.  D00ds also don't appreciate &quot;junky&quot; armor &amp;/or will ask for more.  There have been a few, very few, times I have gotten a &quot;thank you&quot; to heal/buff &amp; then all subsequent responses in a mostly d00d venacular, but even those listened when I told them that most bodies here perfer full words and sentences in conversations and responded accordingly.<br><br>I have, however, been pleasantly surprised by the number of new to EQ entirely younglings I have found.  Mayhap I am lucky?  (or mayhap it is my long standing bane to be one destined to help the questors, those looking for understanding).<br><br>-Caillou Kyrielle, wood elf ranger of 22 seasons<br>-Tiyala, half-elf bard of 8 seasons<br>&lt;Grand New Adventure&gt;<br><br>sorry for the windy response... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=skyknight>Skyknight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Joyful Bard</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/5/02 3:31:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=h